Currently memory, disk and read-only caches are implemented:
MemoryCachedQueriesContainer implements a memory cache. This can be used for fast access to recent queries, although it should be kept in mind that the operating system may swap the overallocated memory thus slowing it down significantly – in such case it is more reasonable to add a disk cache instead.
An example of a memory container entry in cache configuration file is given below:
@insert-file.mem-cache@
ZIPCachedQueriesContainer implements a disk cache. Compressed data is saved to a filesystem folder. The location of the folder is given either as absolute path (absolute-dir element), web application's context-relative path (context-relative-dir element) or system temporary directory (use-system-temp set to true). The folder must be designed for use by the cache only – it must not contain any other files.
An example of a disk container entry in cache configuration file is given below:
@insert-file.disk-cache@
ZIPCachedQueriesContainer can also be used in a read-only mode as a constant cache. This mode is especially useful for demonstrating certain &carrot; features on precached queries. Set read-only &xml; element to true in order to prevent the cache container from saving files. Note that it makes sense to place a read-only cache at the end of the caches cascade (since elements will always be immediately dropped from a read-only cache.
An example of a read-only container entry in cache configuration file is given below:
@insert-file.ro-cache@

